This gauge is based (a Remix) on the Dualstrustion nozzle leveling Fixture by einer_designs: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:23013. That Thing is meant for leveling extruder nozzles on a Rep 1 Dual, but I found that it would not work for aligning nozzles on the Rep 2X, either the OEM mounting block, or Carl Raffle's new cooling block. This can be used for either design. Nozzles are adjusted until both are touching the surface of the tool, while the mounting block is held tightly against the tool.

This Thing was created based on the example of einer_designs Dualstrustion nozzle leveling Fixture.  Since I could see that it would not work for what I had to do to upgrade my MakerBot Replicator 2X, I Remixed it to meet those needs.  You should print this Thing in ABS (the main material used with the Rep 2X) and scale it 101.5%.  This will allow for shrinkage.  I would lay the design on its side (so that no support is needed) and for a clean surface with Kapton tape, do not use a raft.  Any slight flash should be removed if it might interfere with accurate alignment to the mounting block.  
In use this tool should give you a reference for aligning both extruder nozzles the same distance from the gantry when they are mounted on the aluminum mounting block, and it in turn is mounted on the gantry carriage.  Any slight adjustments after that can be achieved by using fine shims under one end of the mounting block or the other.  Care should be used to make sure when the nozzles are next used in leveling the build plate, to make sure that during the beginning of the leveling process, the build plate doesn't crash into the nozzles.  The leveling screws should be turned in all the way before this is done, and if necessary, a shim may be used to activate the stop switch earlier in the build plate's movement.

comments.text: I found that this design puts the nozzles much higher into the block than the standard height they are set.  I actually used this gage on Carl's block and set my MakerBot MK8 nozzles.  Later I tried to put it back on the original R2X MakerBot block with the pre-set nozzle heights and it was almost .25" off from their stock height.

Galactic credits to Brainrelates for his Single SD Memory card holder design. Here are my remixes with a few changes.

  1. Tightened up the dimensions for a snug fit.
  2. Reduced wall thickness from 1.0 mm to 0.8 mm for printing with a 0.4 mm nozzle.

  4. Reduced the cutout for strength and removed it from the back side.
  5. Filleted the corners of the cutout to prevent injuries and lawsuits.
  6. Created a key ring version as requested by BioLumo in comments. The loop protrudes 0.4 mm into the path of the SD card, to prevent it from sliding out in your pocket. Use a fingernail in the groove at the top of the SD card to remove it.

description.text:
Remix of enginecogs wonderful Frankenstein Bust. I wanted less of the cartoon style and something more of a brute, so I have changed the proportions of the head in several ways. I also noticed that the neck bolts were not symmetrical in the original version, either for the individual bolts themselves or in relation to each other. I removed the original bolts completely and added a shaft where you can use actual metal bolts. These will be at a perfect angle, providing a more artificial look with no slop.

I also replaced the base of the bust completely to make it look heavier and less like a chess piece. To better fit the base I also rounded the shoulders.

The model is made to fit M8 neck bolts, with the hole slightly tighter than that. You can either drill the hole larger or use a tap - you might be able to simply screw the bolts in place, possibly by heating the bolt. For using smaller bolts, scale the model accordingly.

Photos show a print at 62.5% scale, 0.1mm layer height, printed at 40mm/s with 20% infill in PETG and using M5 bolts.

title: Inductrix / TinyWhoop - Easy to print, plug-and-play frame replacement

description.text:
After less than two days I broke my Inductrix frame while flying around the house. Made a repair and later broke it again. Time to look at printing a replacement.

I tried a bunch of designs that I found here, and I found that they were either too annoying to print (lots of supports required making messy prints), or had designs that I didn't like for some other reason (most often the ducts).

I've been playing with NACA airfoils for a while in both OpenSCAD and Fusion360, so decided to dig into that. Some online research led me to the NACA7312 airfoil for ducts, so I combined that with a frame that prints flat, with no supports required.

It is basically a drop in replacement for the stock frame. The screw pins are in the same place, but the ducts are a bit different, so you may have to flex it a bit to get the flight controller in there, but once you get it past the edges of the duct, it fits perfectly.

For a mullet-style camera mount, I recommend my TinyWhoop Camera/Vtx mount (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1842589) but anything that fits the stock inductrix screw holes should work with this frame. As the title says, it is plug-and-play!

It has two T-shaped connectors sticking out from the side of the battery plate if you want to reduce weight and use some small rubber bands (e.g. "loom bands") to hold the battery in place. If you want to hold the battery more like the original Inductrix, you can cut those off and use the battery clip that Mr_Disintegrator created for his design:

http://www.thingiverse.com/download:2858356

While this frame was inspired by Mr_Disintegrator's design, it was created from scratch in heavily parameterized OpenSCAD. I'm not quite ready to post the scad file because I'm still tweaking it for other motor and prop sizes, but I will at some point.

This design is optimized for printing with a 0.4mm nozzle, 0.2mm layer height, 1 shell and 0% infill. The frame beams, the stators and the motor holders are 0.8mm so will print solid, while the duct will print hollow in the thicker parts to reduce weight. I strongly recommend printing it in ABS to reduce weight (~25% lighter than PLA). My prints in ABS with these settings are coming in around 4.5g, which is a bit more than the stock Inductrix but less than the Eachine frame.

Since this is printed with only 1 shell and parts of the ducts are hollow, you may get some gaps, holes or zits on the sides of the duct. A little careful work with an X-acto will clean up the zits, and I've found that the little gaps (if you have any) don't have any effect.

It's a reinforcement for platform of dremel 3D printer E3D20.

I already tested and it works for me.

Happy building

Long legs designed for mounting on a Picatinny rail as used on the 3DR Iris quadcopter. Two files are provided: a mount and a long leg. These are separate to allow each object to be printed in the best orientation for strength.
For the Iris, these legs should give about 150mm clearance under the body (plenty for a Tarot or similar gimbal)
Sketchup file is included in the downloads so feel free to remix. In particular the mount can be easily adopted to attach other items to the Picatinny rail arms.
Update 19 July 2014:
Added a "springy" leg option originally designed for my T Copter series. An example can be seen in the later part of this video.
Update 26 Nov 2013: Added another style of leg - triangle girder-type construction. This leg is much more rigid that the flat one which might be preferable.
Update 27 Nov 2013: I realized that, unlike the flat leg, the triangle leg could be printed in one piece. Also a short mount still attaches quite firmly so I've included a Tr iLeg v2.stl and updated the sketchup file.
Update 30 Nov 2013: Version 3 of the triangle leg is 20mm shorter and has a bit more bracing where the leg meets the mount. These legs weigh less that 6 grams each (plus another 2 grams for nut and bolt if desired) ...that's about 1/5 the weight of the genuine 3DR long legs.

I printed this using 3 shells which on my printer filled the typical 2.4mm widths used. There's not much infill but for what it's worth I used 30%. I printed in PLA but I'm sure ABS or nylon would be fine/better.
Once printed slide the leg into the mount and run a 3mm drill bit through the holes so they are nice and clean for the bolts.
Notice that one side of the mount is sharp and the other is rounded. Attached the mount to the Picatinny rail by inserting the sharp side first and the press to clip in the rounded side. The mount should clip on quite firmly making the bolt almost optional.
If you need to remove the mount from the rail then lever the rounded side off with a flat screwdriver.
If you want to use bolts then you'll need a 3mm x 30mm bolt for the mount and a 3mm x 16mm bolt for the leg. NOTE: only tighten the bolts very lightly or you may split your print. Particularly for the mount, the bolt is really just there to stop the mount from spreading rather than clamping it hard to the rail.

I made this up, it was never a toy in the GI Joe line. I needed vehicles for Destro's faction and the toys they /did/ sell were ridiculous. Printing is straightforward. Chassis is printed tracks down without support. I had better luck printing the guns horizontal with supports, rather than printing them barrels up.

Much respect and gratitude to the men and women of our Armed Forces (past and present). Your sacrifice allows people like me to live in peace, freedom and make silly little toys like these. People like you are actually "the real American heroes".

title: Fully printable TRS Drawbot for SG90 / MG90

description.text:
This is fully printable version of the TRS Drawbot designed specifically forSG90/ MG90 servos. I started out with the official alu design and S3003 servos but thought it would be more fun to create a 3D printable version, so I haven't finished the alu version yet. After some revisions it was good enough to share here. I've designed it for the 'official' 4 inch arm size, so it is out of the box compatible with the software from the original TRS Drawbot (google it).

I also had problems controlling the servos with my regular headphone jack. Instead I used an 'el cheapo' usb audio device (the '3D sound' ones that don't have decoupling capacitors) and that worked perfectly.

There is a hole on the base for a 3.5mm audio jack and a small hole for a 3mm screw to secure the marker or pencil. The design is printed and tested. The servo arms are a tight fit so they might need tweaking for other printers. That's why the Openscad file is included. Not much comments though.

I've used an SG90 model from thingiverse to clarify the layout, all credits to the designer of that (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:787942). It doesn't seem to fit though, my own bare servo design is a snug fit, but not as nice for the picture.

I hate using supports so it's all designed to be easily printable without supports. However, if your printer has trouble with the overhangs for the servo arms it might be necessary to flip the pencil holder on the elbow.

I've also added an arm with extra length for possible counterweight for those who would want to try.

I've included a bigger base plate to improve sticking for the servo base; had some issues with that, but I think that might be filament quality related.
After printing use scissors or knife to remove the excess base plate. Screw the base on a piece of wood (approx 20x15 cm). Google the original TRS drawbot for software and other mounting tips.

comments.text: As requested, I have uploaded a picture of the first drawing with the TRS software. You shouldn't expect much from the quality, since the servos aren't that accurate and neither is the audio samplerate. I've only done a few tests with the TRS software; because I felt the resolution of audio is lacking I soon started writing some Python code for Raspberry Pi to control the servos from svgs; that works much better (HW PWM, that is). This also gives possibility for third servo for pen lift and multiple paths. The Stipplegen software works fine, but it's a pain to get the Drawbot wave software working, as it is in C#. description.text:
Dremel Flex-Shaft + MakerBot + MakerBeam + OpenSCAD = (Micro CNC Mill | Drill Press)
Expect future refinements, but this is the first version that works on my Batch 1 MakerBot.

• Print off a Dremel Flex-Shaft Mount (DFM_20100223.stl)

  • Tap a 1/2"-20 thread in the centre hole for the Dremel Flex-Shaft.

  • Print off two MakerBeam-to-M5 Bolt adapter parts (DFB_20100223.stl)

  • Tap the top two Mini-T M3 bolt holes on all printed parts with an M3 or 1/8" thread.

  • Insert the M3 T-bolts from the inside.

  • Loosely bolt M3 nuts on the outside.

  • Clean out Mini-T square holes and press Mini-T parts in.

    Note: Even though the Mini-T square holes are 10.1mm in length and width, you may need to tweak skeinforge to print them large enough or be prepared to whittle out the excess.

  • Tighten the Mini-T M3 nuts, screw in the Dremel Flex-Shaft, bolt the assembly on your Z-platform with M5 bolts.

  • Rev your Dremel!

Printing Tips:

Updated Nov 30, 2016: included a file hair_top_no_support which can be substituted for hair_top if you prefer to use your own support.

1-No supports are required.
..
2-I used a brim on a few pieces, use your discretion based on your own preference:
-jacket is printed upside down to avoid supports, however this results in a smaller base
-the legs are tallish with a small base
-do NOT print the eyes with a brim
..
3-The eyes pieces contain the eyebrow and are quite small. I printed multiple copies at the same time with no brim and they came out perfect, however this part could be tricky if you have problems with bed adhesion.
..
4-hair_top contains a built in support structure that needs to be removed after printing.
..
5-In case anyone wonders how I align pieces for printing, one major consideration (besides printing without supports) is how to avoid layer stepping. For pieces that have slow curves, the smoothest finish is to have the curve vertical instead of horizontal. This is why I always have a head piece printed vertical, even if there is a much simpler way to print it.
..
6-For printing the words with a white background and black lettering, see my full instructions included with the quotes from the Dilbert series:
http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1727898
..
Assembly tips:
-The diagrams below will help in assembling the model and is quite straightforward.
-The model is meant to be glued together.
-Since there are a number of smallish pieces, some of the pieces have tight clearances. Take care to ensure that the first layer 'squish' and any added brim is completely cleaned off.
-The head only has a minimal dent for the eyes which are to be used as placement markers for aligning and gluing the eyes.
-When assembling and gluing the right hand/cuff into the jacket, be sure the hand has the briefcase already hanging off it but not glued. There is no room to insert the briefcase after the hand/cuff/jacket has dried.
-Remove the built in support structure from hair_top before assembly (fairly obvious but here for completeness!)
-Be sure to completely test fit the head/jacket/hair/shirt combo before gluing any of the pieces.
-The bottom of the skirt has the thicker side in the back. The holes for the legs will then be slightly further back.
-It's easy to get the left/right legs and shoes mixed up. Sorry, but the pieces are small and there was not much room for distinction.

title: Bridge for Brio / IKEA Lillabo wooden train tracks
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
UPDATE Nov.,17th 2016:

  • added a stackable version (won't print without supports though!)

RELEASE notes:

Wooden train track element - can be used as a bridge or stacked on top of Brio's original stacking train support (will not serve as a support itself due to minor design differences).

You'll need two sides and one track for a functioning element obviously.

The track element comes in two flavours:

  • flat - easier to print, downside: no clearence for very tall crossing trains to pass underneath the element

  • arched - looks a tiny bit nicer (if you know how to print supports properly), downside: needs supports or has to be printed vertically, still no guarantee, that there's enough space for crossing trains underneath (Brio's equivalent suffers from the same limitations)

Printer:

Taront3rD

Rafts:

No

Supports:

Yes

Resolution:

200 microns

Infill:

25%

Use a 3mm drill to clean out the holes in the side elements. Do NOT drill into the screw holes in the track element!

Use M3x15 (or shorter) screws to attach the two side elements to the track element.

My girlfriend kept nagging me about how I should put my printer to good use and my son wanted some track elements to play with, so I had no choice... ;)

Designed with a caliper rule and Autodesk Fusion 360 (first real project actually) ...aaaaand lots of love!

description.text: Just a little side project I worked on to mount a webcam to an Ultimaker 2+. Just attach some double sided adhesive to the bottom of the square base, pick your corner, and you're good to go!

Printer Brand:

Ultimaker

Printer:

Ultimaker 2

Rafts:

Doesn't Matter

Supports:

Doesn't Matter

Infill:

50% (Dense)

Notes:

This was printed with a 0.4 mm nozzle, on the High Quality preset (0.06 mm), in blue PLA. Sliced in Cura 2.3.1. Combined print time on all 3 parts took around 2 hours.

Only use high quality for this print!! The screw holes are extremely tiny, and the tolerances on this part are extremely low as well.

Finishing Touches

The finished product, in its final sitting form, already required copious amounts of sanding, trimming, filing, and other massaging to get everything to fit.

Make sure to take a lot of material off the connector piece once you finish printing; I ended up with about 1mm of extra material on the side that made the part not fit right.

IF you're using the included screws with the webcam after disassembly, make sure to use the silver long screws and cut down the top screwholes mounting the holder to the PCB by about a millimeter.

Design

Created in SolidWorks 2016. Mocked up from scratch, started off with creating the PCB sketch for reference, mapped all the screw holes correctly for the holder, and went off from there.

description.text:
I've created a 1/12th scale RC Truck/Truggy that features AWD by 4 powered wheel hubs and 4 Brushless Motors.
With room for a mini flight controller, you can perform mixing on the fly and traction control.

I just got my motors in and I am printing now. Tires print well in tpu or ninjaflex, everything else in 100% ABS or PETG, or at least 3 perimeters and 70%.

Total weight estimated in s3d is 1.2 lbs or .55 kilo, or with electronics and battery, just under 2 lbs or 1 kilo.

There are two versions of the motor hubs, depending on where your motor wires exit the base, mine are to the left. The wider set of holes for motor mounting are the top and bottom holes, so print one of each.

This car is designed for 22xx Motors, currently I have NTM Prop Drive 28-30S 800KV which are actually 2216 motors with a 3 hole mounting for a prop adapter. Instead of mounting the prop adapter, I have designed this to direct mount to the wheels providing ~300watts of power to each wheel.

In its current configuration, this RC should reach 85+ mph on 3s provided it stays together, which it won't, so use 2s and get 50 and stability.

I have included a wheel design V3 with a 4 bolt pattern for 3508 T-motors that do not fit the printable tires, but rather standard 1/12 scale truck tires such as: http://www.banggood.com/HBX-112-12054-Off-Road-Tires-WSponge-Inserted-For-12812-p-1029293.html

Full Electronics list v1:
4X NTM 28-30s 800kv motors.
4X FVT littlebee 20A esc, programed in BLheli suite for bidirectional usage.
1X high power (8Kg+) metal gear standard size servo.
1x CC3D Atom Flight Controller with Straight pins.
1x Power Distribution Board, standard 30.5 mounting with BEC of 5v 2A+.
1x Small PPM or S.Bus (I.Bus for Flysky) receiver.
1x Transmitter to match receiver.
1x 2s 1800 mah LiPo battery for 10+ minutes of driving.

description.text:
A modified spool design, originally coming from user dstewartrobots. This was modified for FTC Team 3736 (Serious Business) with a few notable improvements:

  1. This model features 8mm sunk screw heads on the top and bottom. That way, a normal tetrix long screw can fit all the way through, and leave enough room for it to screw into parts on the other side.

  2. It includes two integrated holes for putting medium sized screws through, and allows them to be drilled into the flat part of a bar.

  3. It includes a little hole where you can put the string through, for your convenience. c:

Printer Brand:

Ultimaker

Printer:

Ultimaker 2

Rafts:

Doesn't Matter

Supports:

Doesn't Matter

Infill:

50% (Dense)

Notes:

This was printed on an Ultimaker 2+ with a 0.6 mm nozzle, on the Normal Quality preset (0.15 mm), in grey PLA. Sliced in Cura 2.3.1.

Clean-up

Right now, the three major things you have to focus on for cleaning up the print:

  1. Filing the inside holes to remove any overhang/loose material strands.
  2. Drilling out the two holes on top with a 1/6" drill bit (I believe).
  3. Opening up the wire hole on the side of the top.

All this can be finished in 10 minutes with an xacto knife, sandpaper, and a small enough file to push through the holes.

Design

Started off with dstewartrobots' design, imported into SolidWorks 2016, and modified all manually.
